    <h1>The 80s</h1>
    <h2 id="groupa">Group A</h2>
    <h3>The return to reality</h3>
    <figure>
        <img src="images/lanciaDelta.jpg" />
        <figcaption>Lancia Delta Integrale</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>After the end of the dangerous Group B era in 1986, the World Rally Championship moved into a new phase with the introduction of Group A regulations. These rules were much stricter, requiring
        manufacturers to base their rally cars much more closely on production road cars. This reduced costs and, most importantly, improved safety for both drivers and spectators. While the cars were
        less extreme than their Group B predecessors, they were still highly competitive and technologically advanced.
</p>
    <p>Manufacturers quickly adapted to the new rules, and one car stood above the rest: the Lancia Delta Integrale. Built with all-wheel drive and a turbocharged engine, it proved to be incredibly effective
        on all surfaces. Lancia dominated the late 1980s and early 1990s, winning multiple consecutive manufacturers’ titles and setting a record that still stands today. The Group A era brought stability back
        to the sport, while still delivering exciting and competitive rally action.</p>


    <h2 id="rivalry">The Rivalry</h2>
    <h3>Subaru vs Mitsubishi</h3>

    <figure>
        <img src="images/evo6.jpg" />
        <figcaption>Mitsubishi Evo VI</figcaption>
    </figure>
    
    <p>
        As the 1990s progressed, a new and exciting rivalry began to define the WRC: Subaru vs Mitsubishi. Both manufacturers developed highly capable all-wheel-drive rally cars that became legends in their own right.
        Subaru introduced the Subaru Impreza WRX, while Mitsubishi competed with the powerful Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution series. These cars were not only successful in rallying, but also became popular road cars, helping
        to grow the sport’s global appeal.
    </p>

    <figure>
        <img src="images/impreza.jpg" />
        <figcaption>Subaru Impreza</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
        The rivalry was fueled by intense competition between teams and drivers, with each pushing the other to improve. Subaru focused on balance and handling, while Mitsubishi emphasized power and durability. Their battles
        played out across all types of rallies, from fast gravel stages to tight mountain roads. This competition helped define the identity of 1990s rallying and introduced a new generation of fans to the sport.
    </p>


  
  
  <h2 id="heros">The Heroes of the 90s</h2>
  <h3>Drivers of precision and passion</h3>
    <figure>
        <img src="images/mcrea.jpg" />
        <figcaption>Colin Mcrea</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>The 1990s produced a new generation of rally drivers who combined raw speed with greater control and consistency. With safer and more predictable cars than in the Group B era, drivers could push harder and compete more
        closely across entire seasons. Among the most famous was Colin McRae, known for his aggressive “flat out” driving style that made him one of the most exciting drivers to watch. Alongside him were stars like Carlos Sainz
        and Tommi Mäkinen, who brought consistency, intelligence, and determination to the championship.</p>
    
        <p>These drivers became icons not only because of their victories, but because of their personalities and rivalries. McRae’s fearless approach often put him on the edge, while Sainz’s calculated style made him a constant
            title contender. Mäkinen went on to dominate the latter half of the decade, winning multiple championships and proving his mastery of the Mitsubishi Lancer Evolution. Together, they helped shape the modern era of rallying
            and inspired a new generation of drivers and fans around the world.</p>
    
